Digital Epidemiology

Assignment No. 2 - Influenza-like Illness

Giacomo Legnaro

The goal of this assignment is to try and reproduce for Italy the results reported in the article for the USA D.J. McIver & J. S. Brownstein (2014), "Wikipedia Usage Estimates Prevalence of Influenza-Like Illness in the United States in Near Real-Time", PLoS Comput Biol 10(4): http://journals.plos.org/ploscompbiol/article?id=10.1371/journal.pcbi.1003581

Official data on influenza in Italy are collected by the "Istituto Superiore di Sanità" with a program called "Influnet" that uses sentinel doctors. The project is described here: http://www.iss.it/iflu/index.php?lang=1&anno=2016&tipo=4

These data will be our ground truth.

To reproduce the paper we download page view counts from wikipedia of such keywords related to flu.

Let's start with import all the libraries needed.

Section 1¶

Wikipedia download data¶

First part of this assignment is dedicated to downloads the data from Wikipedia. I have decided to download locally all the data that i'm interested to and only after process them. In this notebook the output of this part will not be full but only a initial printout. All the data are downloaded and analyze with this code. (You can run it only modifying the path. Storage size requested to download all the data locally ~3TB, fibre connection DL:70Mb/s UL:20Mb/s, data download speed 50-65Mb/s)

Limit in download speed and simultaneously number of download files¶

One of the problem that I have encounter with the download of the data from https://dumps.wikimedia.org is due to a limited file download speed give from wikimedia and a limit of 3 simultaneously download for each browser. To bypass this limits, I have written the code so that the downloads are parallelized with the use of different "browser" only with send a different user-agent string. The number of file download simultaneously for each browser are limited at 2 times number of browser because map function not apply the function in a certain order but randomly, and the mod mode to assign the user-agent string is not so efficient in this case. In case of more than 3 file use the same browser, the downloads of the extra file will be interrupt at the begin and the size of this file will be equal to '213'. In this case try-catch with a while loop permit to sleep 2-seconds and retry to download.

Issue with external HD¶

Download all the files locally require a lot of large transfers and is not possible to use directly an external HD (I have tried it and it go slowly, with error, and reduce a lot the speed). So, I have download every month in my pc and also after that I have transfer all the files in the external HD.

Wikimedia empty files¶

One other problem is the presence of empty file, this case are treated separately with relax of some constraint impose in the rest of the downloads.

Wikimedia raw data¶

From 2015-05 Wikimedia datasets is getting produced by stripping down extra-information from Pagecounts-all-sites. This required a change in the path from pagecounts-raw up to 2015-04 to pageviews from 2015-05.

Data collected¶

The data collected are from 2011-10-01 up to 2016-04-30: 5 Influenza seasons.

In [2]:
def makeDirectory(path):
    """
    Return the directory path where save the documents

    :param path: path where create the new folder
    :param directory: name of the new folder
    """
    try:
        os.makedirs(os.path.join(path))
    except OSError:
        if not os.path.isdir(os.path.join(path)):
            raise
    return os.path.join(path)

def download_data(yr,mth,l_dl):
    path = yr + '/' + mth + '/' + l_dl
    urllib.URLopener.version = user_agents[link_dl.index(l_dl)%len(user_agents)]
    wikimedia = urllib.URLopener() 
    headers = {"Content-Length": '213'}
    while int(headers["Content-Length"]) < 5000: 
        try:
            filename, headers = wikimedia.retrieve(main_url + path, '/Users/giacomolegnaro/Downloads/Wikimedia/' + l_dl)
        except IOError:
            time.sleep(2)
    print(yr + ' ' + mth + ' ' + l_dl + ' - Progress ' + str(round(float(len(os.listdir('/Users/giacomolegnaro/Downloads/Wikimedia/'))) / len(link_dl)*100, 2))+'%')

for yr in ['2016']:
    for m in ['-04','-03','-02','-01']:
        mth = yr + m

        if (yr == '2016') or ((yr == '2015') and (m not in ['-01', '-02', '-03', '-04'])):
            sel = 'pageviews'
        else:
            sel = 'pagecounts-raw'
        main_url = 'https://dumps.wikimedia.org/other/' + sel + '/'
        print(yr + ' ' + mth)
        r = requests.get(main_url + yr + '/' + mth + '/')
        soup = BeautifulSoup(r.content, "html.parser")
        link_dl = [link.get('href').encode('utf8') for link in soup.find_all('a') if ((link.get('href') == link.string) and (link.string.split('-')[0] == sel.split('-')[0]))]
        print len(link_dl)
        makeDirectory('/Users/giacomolegnaro/Downloads/Wikimedia/')
        makeDirectory('/Volumes/My Book/Wikimedia/' + sel + '/' + yr + '/' + mth + '/')

        p = Pool(len(user_agents)*2)

        out = p.map(lambda l_dl: download_data(yr,mth,l_dl), link_dl)

        path = yr + '/' + mth + '/'
        source = '/Users/giacomolegnaro/Downloads/Wikimedia/'
        dest = '/Volumes/My Book/Wikimedia/' + sel + '/'
        out = [shutil.move(source + f,dest + path + f) for f in os.listdir(source)]

for yr in ['2015','2014','2013','2012']:
    for m in ['-12','-11','-10','-04','-03','-02','-01']:
        mth = yr + m

        if (yr == '2016') or ((yr == '2015') and (m not in ['-01', '-02', '-03', '-04'])):
            sel = 'pageviews'
        else:
            sel = 'pagecounts-raw'
        main_url = 'https://dumps.wikimedia.org/other/' + sel + '/'
        print(yr + ' ' + mth)
        r = requests.get(main_url + yr + '/' + mth + '/')
        soup = BeautifulSoup(r.content, "html.parser")
        link_dl = [link.get('href').encode('utf8') for link in soup.find_all('a') if ((link.get('href') == link.string) and (link.string.split('-')[0] == sel.split('-')[0]))]
        print len(link_dl)
        makeDirectory('/Users/giacomolegnaro/Downloads/Wikimedia/')

    for m in ['-12','-11','-10']:
        mth = yr + m

        if (yr == '2016') or ((yr == '2015') and (m not in ['-01', '-02', '-03', '-04'])):
            sel = 'pageviews'
        else:
            sel = 'pagecounts-raw'
        main_url = 'https://dumps.wikimedia.org/other/' + sel + '/'
        print(yr + ' ' + mth)
        r = requests.get(main_url + yr + '/' + mth + '/')
        soup = BeautifulSoup(r.content, "html.parser")
        link_dl = [link.get('href').encode('utf8') for link in soup.find_all('a') if ((link.get('href') == link.string) and (link.string.split('-')[0] == sel.split('-')[0]))]
        print len(link_dl)

def download_data(yr,mth,l_dl):
    path = yr + '/' + mth + '/' + l_dl
    urllib.URLopener.version = user_agents[link_dl.index(l_dl)%len(user_agents)]
    wikimedia = urllib.URLopener() 
    wikimedia.retrieve(main_url + path, '/Users/giacomolegnaro/Downloads/Wikimedia/' + l_dl)
    print(yr + ' ' + mth + ' ' + l_dl + ' - Progress ' + str(round(float(len(os.listdir('/Users/giacomolegnaro/Downloads/Wikimedia/'))) / len(link_dl)*100, 2))+'%')

Section 2¶

Wikipedia analyze data¶

Second part of this notebook is dedicated to the analyze of the download files. Each month required to comment the row code free and uncomment the desired month.

(The code is reported in one chunck - mainly algorithm - and is request to comment/uncomment only PATH_TO_FILE for each month)

Note: This code work only with macOS system. The 'gzcat' function to ungzip the file request masOS Operating System.

Slow analyze¶

One of the limit in the speed of the analyze is due to the read speed from an external HD (USB 3.0) but in this case nothing is possible to reduce it.

Ungzip the file and read row by row required ~30 seconds for each file, too much! With 'gzcat' function I have reduce a lot the time to unzip (~1-2 seconds).

Another limit is due to read all the rows of the file! This is not necessary! I have open and read some random files and I have seen thata it start always after 3500000 rows, and with the function islice from itertools I have reduce a lot the computational time. Similarly to the jump at 3500000 I have think is not necessary to read all the rows after, and when 'it' is no more the row start, I have dropped down the analyze and go to the next file.

At the end, the time for each file go from 2 to 5 seconds.

'it' and 'it.m'¶

I have read in the wikimedia page https://dumps.wikimedia.org/other/pagecounts-raw/, open and read some random files and I have found that 'it.m' is not the page views from mobile devices but of wikimedia project. 'it.mw' is the correct views from the wikipedia mobile devices, but this views are not for each page, but aggregated! In this study I have only considered the 'it' page views.

Chronology wikipedia pages¶

Yes, another problem! Sometimes the page are subject to a merge with other pages, or to a change of the name, or some other things. I assume are not all, but I will report below some things:

  • 13:53, 6 dic 2013 "Gambo7 ha spostato la pagina Virus dell'influenza A sottotipo H1N1 a Influenzavirus A sottotipo H1N1: omologia con Influenzavirus A". In this case an user have changed and merge Virus_dell'influenza_A_sottotipo_H1N1 into Influenzavirus_A_sottotipo_H1N1 due to a homology with Influenzavirus_A
  • Virus_dell'influenza_A_sottotipo_H1N1 vs Virus_dell%27influenza_A_sottotipo_H1N1 issue with the superscript character "'"
  • 19:56, 7 nov 2011 "Doc.mari ha spostato Vaccino influenzale a Vaccino antinfluenzale". In this case the user have changed the name from Vaccino_influenzale to Vaccino_antinfluenzale. I have seen this things too late. The series is affected by this anomaly at the beginning

Another things about wikipedia keywords search: '#' indicate the section in a page, but the data available reported only the total page and not the single section. (e.g. Vaccino_antinfluenzale#Vaccino_influenza_stagionale)

Analyze data¶

The keyword list above are searched in each file; when they are founded, they have the number of views in the third column. I have created a file for each keywords and at each occur I update the files with the date in format YYYYMMDDHHMMSS follow by the page views value (third column in each row of the gzip file) and a '\n' character.

An extra file I have created to saved all the page views in Italy: 'totalViews'.

# PATH_TO_FILE = '/Volumes/My Book/Wikimedia/pageviews/2015'

FILE_DIR = '/Users/giacomolegnaro/Documents/Data Science/2nd Year/Digital Epidemiology/Homework2/Wikimedia/clean'
In [18]:
for dirname, dirnames, filenames in os.walk(PATH_TO_FILE):
    for subdirname in dirnames:
        print subdirname
        for gzip_path in glob.glob(os.path.join(dirname, subdirname) + "/*.gz"):
            fileName = gzip_path.split('/')[-1][:-3].split('-')
            print gzip_path.split('/')[-1][:-3]
            if os.path.isdir(gzip_path) == False:
                p = subprocess.Popen(['gzcat', gzip_path], stdout=subprocess.PIPE, stderr=subprocess.PIPE)
                fh = io_method(p.communicate()[0])
                assert p.returncode == 0
                ct = 0
                for line in islice(fh, 3500000, None):
                    lineList = line.split(' ')
                    if lineList[0] == 'it':
                        try:
                            ct += int(lineList[2])
                        except IndexError:
                            ct += 0
                        if lineList[1] in keywords:
                            with open(FILE_DIR + '/' + lineList[1] + '.txt', 'a') as output:
                                output.write(fileName[1] + fileName[2] + ' ' + lineList[2] + '\n')
                    elif ((lineList[0] != 'it') and (ct != 0)):
                        break
                
                with open (FILE_DIR + '/' 'totalViews.txt','a') as output:
                    output.write(fileName[1] + fileName[2] + ' ' + str(ct) + '\n')

Section 3¶

Process official data on "Influenza" in Italy¶

Data from Influnet surveillance system¶

Influnet series collect data for each year from mid October to mid-April. The file contains a lot of information, too much for us! We consider only the first column Year-Week (YYYY-WW) [ISO_week_date] and the fifth column with the estimated flu incidence for that week.

Issue: The data are with separator character a blank ' ', thousands character dot '.' and comma as decimal ','.

This assumption is not true only in the 2013-2014 season. In this case the thousands character and decimal are invert! With a delete of the series and a new loading with this precaution all is ok.

In [19]:
path_gt = 'influnet/data/'
path = 'Wikimedia/clean/'
In [20]:
gt_ts = pd.concat([pd.read_csv(f, sep=' ', thousands='.', decimal=',', index_col=0, skiprows = 1, usecols=[0,4], names = ['time',f.split('_')[1].split('.')[0]]) for f in glob.glob(path_gt + "/*.txt")], axis=1)
In [21]:
del gt_ts['2013-2014']
In [22]:
f = path_gt + "influnet_2013-2014.txt"
gt_ts = pd.concat([gt_ts, pd.read_csv(f, sep=' ', thousands=',', decimal='.', index_col=0, skiprows = 2, usecols=[0,4], names = ['time',f.split('_')[1].split('.')[0]])], axis=1).sum(axis=1)
gt_ts = gt_ts.fillna(0)
gt_ts_raw = gt_ts.copy()

Plot all the official series, only to a briefly view

gt_ts.plot(legend=True, label='Groud Truth')

The period consider start from the 42th week's of 2011 and we reduce the ground truth series to this period.

Part 1.1¶

Process the Wikipedia pageview data for the "Influenza" page of the Italian¶

Define a function to aggregate the pageviews on a weekly time scale. function strftime works on macOS an with the string "%G-%V" take the datetime and return the Year and Week in ISO calendar (the week start on Monday and the week beetween two years belong to the year with majority of its day - thursday is the tip of the balance)

In [26]:
def hourlyToWeekly(filename, sep):
    ts = pd.Series.from_csv(filename, sep = sep, header=None, index_col = 0)
    wts = ts.groupby(ts.index.strftime("%G-%V")).sum()
    return wts
In [27]:
df = pd.concat([hourlyToWeekly(f, ' ') for f in glob.glob(path + "/*.txt")], axis=1)
df = df.fillna(0)

df.columns = [os.path.basename(f).split('.')[0] for f in glob.glob(path + "/*.txt")]
In [28]:
df["Influenzavirus_A_sottotipo_H1N1"] = df["Influenzavirus_A_sottotipo_H1N1"].add(df["Virus_dell'influenza_A_sottotipo_H1N1"], fill_value=0).add(df["Virus_dell%27influenza_A_sottotipo_H1N1"], fill_value=0)

del df["Virus_dell'influenza_A_sottotipo_H1N1"]
del df["Virus_dell%27influenza_A_sottotipo_H1N1"]

As explained in section 2 we merge the three series:

  • Influenzavirus_A_sottotipo_H1N1
  • Virus_dell'influenza_A_sottotipo_H1N1
  • Virus_dell%27influenza_A_sottotipo_H1N1 and delete the extra
In [29]:
df_raw = df.copy()

The series are downloaded from the beginning of October to the end of April. But the Influnet series are a subset! To compare the two time series, we exctract a subset from the wikipedia data with indexes given by the ground truth.

In [30]:
init_date = min(set(df.index) & set(gt_ts.index))
init_date
Out[30]:
'2011-42'
In [31]:
gt_ts = gt_ts[init_date:]
In [32]:
df = df.loc[gt_ts.index]
In [33]:
df_tot = pd.concat([df, gt_ts], axis=1)

names.append('GroundTruth')
df_tot.columns = names

If we consider only the views is a good idea, but a better idea is to divide the views by the total views. This is done because the series could be affected by a trend of an increase use of wikipedia (to consult).

In [35]:
df_norm = df.divide(df['totalViews'], axis='index')
In [36]:
del df_norm['totalViews']

It's evident a similar evolution of the wikipedia click on page "Influenza" respect to ground truth, but to have an objective indicator we try to compute the correlation between the two time series.

Initially I have consider some measures of correlation:

  • Pearson Correlation
  • Cross Correlation
  • Spearman rank-order Correlation

Let's start to analyze them:

Pearson correlation¶

The Pearson correlation coefficient measures the linear relationship between two datasets. Strictly speaking, Pearson’s correlation requires that each dataset be normally distributed, and not necessarily zero-mean. Like other correlation coefficients, this one varies between -1 and +1 with 0 implying no correlation. Correlations of -1 or +1 imply an exact linear relationship. Positive correlations imply that as x increases, so does y. Negative correlations imply that as x increases, y decreases. The p-value roughly indicates the probability of an uncorrelated system producing datasets that have a Pearson correlation at least as extreme as the one computed from these datasets.

To apply this measure of correlation we try to verify if they are normally distributed, and to do that we use Jarque-Bera test and normal test.

Jarque-Bera test work for a large enough number of data sample (>2000) and the test asymptoticcaly has a Chi-Squared distribution with 2 degrees of freedom.

The null hypothesis H0 is a joint hypothesis of the skewness being zero and the excess kurtosis being zero (kurtosis equal to 3, excess kurtosis equal to 0)

In [39]:
jb_value,p = scipy.stats.jarque_bera(gt_ts)
print 'Ground Truth - Statistic test', round(jb_value,4), 'with', p, 'p-value'

Ground Truth - Statistic test 26.8481 with 1.47912398418e-06 p-value
In [40]:
jb_value,p = scipy.stats.jarque_bera(df_norm['Influenza'])
print 'Influenza - Statistic test', round(jb_value,4), 'with', p, 'p-value'

Influenza - Statistic test 74.3368 with 1.11022302463e-16 p-value

Normal test is based on D’Agostino and Pearson’s test that combines skew and kurtosis to produce an omnibus test of normality.

Obviously the null hypothesis H0 is normal distribution and the test is distributed as a Chi-Square.

In [41]:
k2,p = scipy.stats.mstats.normaltest(gt_ts)
print 'Ground Truth - Statistic test', round(k2,4), 'with', p, 'p-value'

Ground Truth - Statistic test 21.2782 with 2.39607991243e-05 p-value
In [42]:
k2,p = scipy.stats.mstats.normaltest(df_norm['Influenza'])
print 'Influenza - Statistic test', round(k2,4), 'with', p, 'p-value'

Influenza - Statistic test 40.3316 with 1.74624418387e-09 p-value

Both the test Reject the null hypothesis of normal distribution, the correlation measure haven't any sense. Only to play I have tried to do the measure of Pearson correlation

Cross-correlation¶

Relationships between time series is by the cross-correlation function (assuming stationarity). To use this measure we should verify the stationarity of the two series. The null hypothesis is of zero correlation .

To do that I have used the Augmented Dickey-Fuller test. The null hypothesis of the Augmented Dickey-Fuller is that there is a unit root, with the alternative that there is no unit root. If the pvalue is above a critical size, then we cannot reject that there is a unit root.

The p-values are obtained through regression surface approximation from MacKinnon 1994, but using the updated 2010 tables. If the p-value is close to significant, then the critical values should be used to judge whether to accept or reject the null.

In [44]:
adf,pvalue,_,_,_,_ = statsmodels.tsa.stattools.adfuller(gt_ts)
print 'Augmented Dickey-Fuller unit root test - Ground Truth Series'
print 'Test statistic:', round(adf,4), 'with', pvalue, "p-value"

Augmented Dickey-Fuller unit root test - Ground Truth Series
Test statistic: -5.6384 with 1.05025106912e-06 p-value
In [45]:
adf,pvalue,_,_,_,_ = statsmodels.tsa.stattools.adfuller(df_norm['Influenza'])
print 'Augmented Dickey-Fuller unit root test - Influenza Series'
print 'Test statistic:', round(adf,4), 'with', pvalue, "p-value"

Augmented Dickey-Fuller unit root test - Influenza Series
Test statistic: -4.4052 with 0.000290597006878 p-value

For each series we reject the null hypothesis of unit root at level 5% and also 1%. We assume stationarity! This will be the measure of correlation that we use in this assignment.

The function of numpy.correlate and scipy.signal.correlate return an incorrect value of correlation. To solve this I have written the function correctly (I hope).

The function, given two time series in input, return the correlation value, the statistic test and the p-value.

In [46]:
def crossCorr(x,y):
    num = np.mean((x-np.mean(x))*(y-np.mean(y)))
    den = np.std(x)*np.std(y)
    r = num/den
    
    #significance
    n = len(x)
    t = r * ((n-2)/(1-r**2))**(0.5)
    pvalue = 1-scipy.stats.t.cdf(t, n-2)        
    
    return r,t,pvalue
In [47]:
r,t,p = crossCorr(gt_ts, df_norm['Influenza'])

print 'The correlation between Ground Truth and Influenza is:'
print 'Cross-Correlation',round(r,4), 'with statistic test', round(t,4), 'and pvalue', p 

The correlation between Ground Truth and Influenza is:
Cross-Correlation 0.7505 with statistic test 13.339 and pvalue 0.0

The null hypothesis $H_0$ of zero correlation is rejected at every level $\alpha$

Spearman rank-order correlation¶

The Spearman's rank-order correlation is the nonparametric version of the Pearson product-moment correlation. Spearman's correlation coefficient measures the strength and direction of association between two ranked variables and this is not our case!

Note: The measure of correlation that I have used in all of the next point is Cross-Correlation

Part 2.2¶

On aggregating the hourly pageview data to compute weekly pageviews, can you do something to select page views from Italy?¶

Given this question some consideration are acceptable like do a random samples or we can see how the views are distributed during the 24-hours. I'm interesting to follow the second option.

To do that I have defined a function call hourly, this function reload all the data but it aggregated the views by the hour. Every basic treatment of the series explained before are done.

In [49]:
def hourly(filename, sep):
    ts = pd.Series.from_csv(filename, sep = sep, header=None, index_col = 0)
    wts = ts.groupby(ts.index.strftime('%H')).mean()
    return wts
In [50]:
df_h = pd.concat([hourly(f, ' ') for f in glob.glob(path + "/*.txt")], axis=1)
df_h = df_h.fillna(0)

Part 3.1¶

Build a regression model that predicts the Influnet incidence for a given week based on the Wikipedia pageview data for the same week.¶

We should select some feature from the 24-involved. We build a score for each feature given by a mean of four indicator:

  • F-test
  • Mutual Information
  • Cross-Correlation (explained before)

F-test [f_regression function]

The methods based on F-test estimate the degree of linear dependency between two random variables. It is a univariate linear regression tests. Quick linear model for testing the effect of a single regressor, sequentially for many regressors.

This is done in 2 steps:

  • The cross correlation between each regressor and the target is computed, that is,

    ((X[:, i] - mean(X[:, i])) (y - mean_y)) / (std(X[:, i]) std(y))

  • It is converted to an F score then to a p-value.

Mutual Information [mutal_info_regression]

The mutual information methods can capture any kind of statistical dependency, but being nonparametric, they require more samples for accurate estimation. It estimate mutual information for a continuous target variable. Mutual information (MI) between two random variables is a non-negative value, which measures the dependency between the variables. It is equal to zero if and only if two random variables are independent, and higher values mean higher dependency. The function relies on nonparametric methods based on entropy estimation from k-nearest neighbors distances.

In [61]:
# F-test
f_test, _ = f_regression(df_norm,gt_ts)
f_test = normalize([f_test])[0]

# Mutual Information
mi = mutual_info_regression(df_norm,gt_ts)
mi = normalize([mi])[0]

# Cross-Correlation
corr = [crossCorr(gt_ts, df_norm[i])[0] for i in list(df_norm.columns)]
corr = normalize([corr])[0]

# Score
score = np.mean([f_test,mi,corr], axis=0)

t = reg.coef_ / se
p = 2 * (1 - stats.t.cdf(np.abs(t), y_train.shape[0] - X_train.shape[1]))

Cross-validation - Multiple model performance

Now it's time to evaluate the performance of three model with cross-validation.

Generalized Linear Models

The methods involved for regression, the target value is expected to be a linear combination of the input variables.

$\hat{y}(w, x) = w_0 + w_1 x_1 + ... + w_p x_p$

$\hat{y}$ is the predicted value, the vector $w = (w_1,..., w_p)$ as coef and $w_0$ as intercept.

Model selected:

  • Ordinary Least Squares: LinearRegression fits a linear model with coefficients $w = (w_1, ..., w_p)$ to minimize the residual sum of squares between the observed responses in the dataset, and the responses predicted by the linear approximation. $\underset{w}{min\,} {|| X w - y||_2}^2$
  • Ridge Regression: Ridge regression addresses some of the problems of Ordinary Least Squares by imposing a penalty on the size of coefficients. The ridge coefficients minimize a penalized residual sum of squares, $\underset{w}{min\,} {{|| X w - y||_2}^2 + \alpha {||w||_2}^2}$
    Here, $\alpha \geq 0$ is a complexity parameter that controls the amount of shrinkage: the larger the value of $\alpha$, the greater the amount of shrinkage and thus the coefficients become more robust to collinearity.
  • Lasso Regression: The Lasso is a linear model that estimates sparse coefficients. It is useful in some contexts due to its tendency to prefer solutions with fewer parameter values, effectively reducing the number of variables upon which the given solution is dependent. It consists of a linear model trained with $\ell_1$ prior as regularizer. The objective function to minimize is: $\underset{w}{min\,} { \frac{1}{2n_{samples}} ||X w - y||_2 ^ 2 + \alpha ||w||_1}$ The lasso estimate thus solves the minimization of the least-squares penalty with $\alpha ||w||_1$ added, where $\alpha$ is a constant and $||w||_1$ is the $\ell_1$-norm of the parameter vector.

  • Bayesian Regression: Bayesian regression techniques can be used to include regularization parameters in the estimation procedure: the regularization parameter is not set in a hard sense but tuned to the data at hand. This can be done by introducing uninformative priors over the hyper parameters of the model. The $\ell_{2}$ regularization used in Ridge Regression is equivalent to finding a maximum a-postiori solution under a Gaussian prior over the parameters w with precision $\lambda^-1$. Instead of setting lambda manually, it is possible to treat it as a random variable to be estimated from the data. To obtain a fully probabilistic model, the output y is assumed to be Gaussian distributed around
    $X_w$: $p(y|X,w,\alpha) = \mathcal{N}(y|X w,\alpha)$
    Alpha is again treated as a random variable that is to be estimated from the data. The advantages of Bayesian Regression are:

    • It adapts to the data at hand.
    • It can be used to include regularization parameters in the estimation procedure.

    The disadvantages of Bayesian regression include:

    • Inference of the model can be time consuming.
  • Polynomial regression: One common pattern within machine learning is to use linear models trained on nonlinear functions of the data. This approach maintains the generally fast performance of linear methods, while allowing them to fit a much wider range of data. If we want to fit a paraboloid to the data instead of a plane, we can combine the features in second-order polynomials, so that the model looks like this: $\hat{y}(w, x) = w_0 + w_1 x_1 + w_2 x_2 + w_3 x_1 x_2 + w_4 x_1^2 + w_5 x_2^2$
    The observation is that this is still a linear model: imagine creating a new variable $z = [x_1, x_2, x_1 x_2, x_1^2, x_2^2]$
    With this re-labeling of the data, our problem can be written $\hat{y}(w, x) = w_0 + w_1 z_1 + w_2 z_2 + w_3 z_3 + w_4 z_4 + w_5 z_5$
    We see that the resulting polynomial regression is in the same class of linear models we’d considered above (the model is linear in w) and can be solved by the same techniques. By considering linear fits within a higher-dimensional space built with these basis functions, the model has the flexibility to fit a much broader range of data.
In [79]:
kf = KFold(n_splits=10, shuffle=True).split(df_top.index)
models = ['LinearRegression','Ridge','Lasso','Bayesian','Polynomial']
mse = {m:[] for m in models}
alphas = [0.01,0.02,0.05,0.08,0.1,0.2,0.5,0.8,1,2,5,8]
In [80]:
for tr, te in kf:
    X_train = df_top.iloc[tr]
    X_test = df_top.iloc[te]
    y_train = gt_ts.iloc[tr]
    y_test = gt_ts.iloc[te]
    
    ### Ordinary least squares Linear Regression
    reg = linear_model.LinearRegression(fit_intercept=True, normalize=True).fit(X_train,y_train)
    mse['LinearRegression'].append(np.mean((reg.predict(X_test) - y_test) ** 2))
    
    ### Ridge Regression
    ridge_cv = linear_model.RidgeCV(fit_intercept=True, normalize=True, alphas = alphas).fit(X_train, y_train)
    ridge = linear_model.Ridge(fit_intercept=True, normalize=True, alpha = round(ridge_cv.alpha_,3)).fit(X_train, y_train)
    mse['Ridge'].append(np.mean((ridge.predict(X_test) - y_test) ** 2))
    
    ### Lasso Regression
    lasso_cv = linear_model.LassoCV(fit_intercept=True, normalize=True, alphas=alphas).fit(X_train, y_train)
    lasso = linear_model.Lasso(fit_intercept=True, normalize=True, alpha = round(lasso_cv.alpha_,3)).fit(X_train, y_train)
    mse['Lasso'].append(np.mean((lasso.predict(X_test) - y_test) ** 2))
    
    ### Bayesian Ridge Regression
    bay = linear_model.BayesianRidge(fit_intercept=True, normalize=True).fit(X_train, y_train)
    mse['Bayesian'].append(np.mean((bay.predict(X_test) - y_test) ** 2))
    
    ### Polynomial Regression
    pol = Pipeline([('poly', PolynomialFeatures(degree=2)),
                    ('linear', linear_model.LinearRegression(fit_intercept=True, normalize=True))]).fit(X_train, y_train)
    mse['Polynomial'].append(np.mean((pol.predict(X_test) - y_test) ** 2))

Build a model - model 1 - Night hours cut-off¶

In this model I have tried to cut off the night view, in particular from mid-night to 7am include.

In [96]:
def hourlyToWeeklyDropNight(filename,sep,h_start,h_end):
    ts = pd.Series.from_csv(filename, sep = sep, header=None, index_col = 0)
    ts = ts.ix[ts.index.indexer_between_time(datetime.time(h_start),datetime.time(h_end),include_start=True,include_end=True)]
    wts = ts.groupby(ts.index.strftime("%G-%V")).sum()
    return wts

# F-test
f_test, _ = f_regression(df_night,gt_ts)
f_test = normalize([f_test])[0]

# Mutual Information
mi = mutual_info_regression(df_night,gt_ts)
mi = normalize([mi])[0]

# Cross-Correlation
corr = [crossCorr(gt_ts, df_night[i])[0] for i in list(df_night.columns)]
corr = normalize([corr])[0]

# Score
score = np.mean([f_test,mi,corr], axis=0)

kf = KFold(n_splits=10, shuffle=True).split(df_top.index)
models = ['LinearRegression','Ridge','Lasso','Bayesian','Polynomial']
mse = {m:[] for m in models}
alphas = [0.01,0.02,0.05,0.08,0.1,0.2,0.5,0.8,1,2,5,8]
In [112]:
for tr, te in kf:
    X_train = df_top.iloc[tr]
    X_test = df_top.iloc[te]
    y_train = gt_ts.iloc[tr]
    y_test = gt_ts.iloc[te]
    
    ### Ordinary least squares Linear Regression
    reg = linear_model.LinearRegression(fit_intercept=True, normalize=True).fit(X_train,y_train)
    mse['LinearRegression'].append(np.mean((reg.predict(X_test) - y_test) ** 2))
    
    ### Ridge Regression
    ridge_cv = linear_model.RidgeCV(fit_intercept=True, normalize=True, alphas = alphas).fit(X_train, y_train)
    ridge = linear_model.Ridge(fit_intercept=True, normalize=True, alpha = round(ridge_cv.alpha_,3)).fit(X_train, y_train)
    mse['Ridge'].append(np.mean((ridge.predict(X_test) - y_test) ** 2))
    
    ### Lasso Regression
    lasso_cv = linear_model.LassoCV(fit_intercept=True, normalize=True, alphas=alphas).fit(X_train, y_train)
    lasso = linear_model.Lasso(fit_intercept=True, normalize=True, alpha = round(lasso_cv.alpha_,3)).fit(X_train, y_train)
    mse['Lasso'].append(np.mean((lasso.predict(X_test) - y_test) ** 2))
    
    ### Bayesian Ridge Regression
    bay = linear_model.BayesianRidge(fit_intercept=True, normalize=True).fit(X_train, y_train)
    mse['Bayesian'].append(np.mean((bay.predict(X_test) - y_test) ** 2))
    
    ### Polynomial Regression
    pol = Pipeline([('poly', PolynomialFeatures(degree=2)),
                    ('linear', linear_model.LinearRegression(fit_intercept=True, normalize=True))]).fit(X_train, y_train)
    mse['Polynomial'].append(np.mean((pol.predict(X_test) - y_test) ** 2))
In [113]:

    print round(v,5),'\t', k
print '\nThe model with the minimum MSE', min(mse_mean.values()),'is', min(mse_mean, key=mse_mean.get)

The model with the minimum MSE 2.60657161615 is Ridge

As anticipated nothing is changed! Ridge is again the model with the lowest MSE. To not be redundant a lot, we make a prediction only with an increase train set step-by-step from one observation to all minus one observations. The train set is used to estimate the coefficients of the model. The predictions are done one week out-of-sample of every increasing dataset.

In [114]:
y_pred = []
for i in range(1,len(df_top.index)):
    X_train = df_top.iloc[:i]
    X_test = df_top.iloc[[i]]
    y_train = gt_ts.iloc[:i]
    y_test = gt_ts.iloc[[i]]
    ridge_cv = linear_model.RidgeCV(fit_intercept=True, normalize=True, alphas = alphas).fit(X_train, y_train)
    ridge = linear_model.Ridge(fit_intercept=True, normalize=True, alpha = round(ridge_cv.alpha_,3)).fit(X_train, y_train)
    y_pred.append(ridge.predict(X_test)[0])

Build a model - model 2 - Structural Break¶

At this point we consider the possibilities of a structural break at each season. To consider this case, we introduce one dummy for each season.

We start re-searching the top 5 feature.

In [117]:

sse = np.sum((reg.predict(X_train) - y_train) ** 2, axis=0) / float(X_train.shape[0] - X_train.shape[1])
se = np.array([np.sqrt(np.diagonal(sse * np.linalg.inv(np.dot(X_train.T, X_train))))])
t = reg.coef_ / se
p = 2 * (1 - stats.t.cdf(np.abs(t), y_train.shape[0] - X_train.shape[1]))

Build a model - model 3 - Shift¶

In this model we dig up the strange thing that we have seen in the part 2.1: Vaccino_antinfluenzale seems to have an high correlation with ground truth but it require a shift. To not limit the shift only to Vaccino_antinfluenzale series we extend this approach to all series. In particular we compute the cross-correlation between ground truth and each series with shift varying from 0 to 20.

To have more completed series we reload the raw dataframe with values from the beginning of October to the end of April.

In [136]:
df_shift = df_raw.copy()

df_shift_norm = df_shift.divide(df_shift['totalViews'], axis='index')
del df_shift_norm['totalViews']
df_shift_norm.fillna(0, inplace=True)
In [147]:
c_shift = {c:[] for c in df_shift_norm.columns}
c_s_idx = {c:[] for c in df_shift_norm.columns}
for c in df_shift_norm.columns:
    c_shift[c].append([crossCorr(gt_ts, df_shift_norm[c].shift(i)[gt_ts.index].fillna(0))[0] for i in range(20)])
    c_s_idx[c].append(c_shift[c][0].index(max(c_shift[c][0], key=abs)))

And now tried to fit a model, and see if this is better than the previous. and if there is some changing in the top 5 feature.

In [159]:
# F-test
f_test, _ = f_regression(df_shift_norm,gt_ts)
f_test = normalize([f_test])[0]

# Mutual Information
mi = mutual_info_regression(df_shift_norm,gt_ts)
mi = normalize([mi])[0]

# Cross-Correlation
corr = [crossCorr(gt_ts, df_shift_norm[i])[0] for i in list(df_shift_norm.columns)]
corr = normalize([corr])[0]

# Score
score = np.mean([f_test,mi,corr], axis=0)

sort_index_corr = sorted(range(len(corr)), key=np.abs(corr).__getitem__, reverse=True)
sort_index_score = sorted(range(len(score)), key=np.abs(score).__getitem__, reverse=True)

In [169]:
kf = KFold(n_splits=10, shuffle=True).split(df_top.index)
models = ['LinearRegression','Ridge','Lasso','Bayesian','Polynomial']
mse = {m:[] for m in models}
alphas = [0.01,0.02,0.05,0.08,0.1,0.2,0.5,0.8,1,2,5,8]
In [170]:
for tr, te in kf:
    X_train = df_top.iloc[tr]
    X_test = df_top.iloc[te]
    y_train = gt_ts.iloc[tr]
    y_test = gt_ts.iloc[te]
    
    ### Ordinary least squares Linear Regression
    reg = linear_model.LinearRegression(fit_intercept=True, normalize=True).fit(X_train,y_train)
    mse['LinearRegression'].append(np.mean((reg.predict(X_test) - y_test) ** 2))
    
    ### Ridge Regression
    ridge_cv = linear_model.RidgeCV(fit_intercept=True, normalize=True, alphas = alphas).fit(X_train, y_train)
    ridge = linear_model.Ridge(fit_intercept=True, normalize=True, alpha = round(ridge_cv.alpha_,3)).fit(X_train, y_train)
    mse['Ridge'].append(np.mean((ridge.predict(X_test) - y_test) ** 2))
    
    ### Lasso Regression
    lasso_cv = linear_model.LassoCV(fit_intercept=True, normalize=True, alphas=alphas).fit(X_train, y_train)
    lasso = linear_model.Lasso(fit_intercept=True, normalize=True, alpha = round(lasso_cv.alpha_,3)).fit(X_train, y_train)
    mse['Lasso'].append(np.mean((lasso.predict(X_test) - y_test) ** 2))
    
    ### Bayesian Ridge Regression
    bay = linear_model.BayesianRidge(fit_intercept=True, normalize=True).fit(X_train, y_train)
    mse['Bayesian'].append(np.mean((bay.predict(X_test) - y_test) ** 2))
    
    ### Polynomial Regression
    pol = Pipeline([('poly', PolynomialFeatures(degree=2)),
                    ('linear', linear_model.LinearRegression(fit_intercept=True, normalize=True))]).fit(X_train, y_train)
    mse['Polynomial'].append(np.mean((pol.predict(X_test) - y_test) ** 2))

for i in range(k):
    acf = statsmodels.tsa.stattools.acf(df_top[df_top.columns[i]], alpha=0.05)[0]
    pacf = statsmodels.tsa.stattools.pacf(df_top[df_top.columns[i]], alpha=0.05)[0]
    a,b = pos[i*2]

All the feature (Ground Truth included) have a sinusoid autocorrelation, while the partial have only the first two lag significant (out of the boundarie). I think that an ARMA(1,1) could solve it, but we considera an AR(1) process (as request in the assignment) and see how the residuals are correlated

    for i in range(k):

names.append('GroundTruth_lag1')

In [329]:
kf = KFold(n_splits=10, shuffle=True).split(df_ar.index)
models = ['LinearRegression','Ridge','Lasso','Bayesian','Polynomial']
mse = {m:[] for m in models}
alphas = [0.01,0.02,0.05,0.08,0.1,0.2,0.5,0.8,1,2,5,8]
In [330]:
for tr, te in kf:
    X_train = df_ar.iloc[tr]
    X_test = df_ar.iloc[te]
    y_train = gt_ts.iloc[tr]
    y_test = gt_ts.iloc[te]
    
    ### Ordinary least squares Linear Regression
    reg = linear_model.LinearRegression(fit_intercept=True, normalize=True).fit(X_train,y_train)
    mse['LinearRegression'].append(np.mean((reg.predict(X_test) - y_test) ** 2))
    
    ### Ridge Regression
    ridge_cv = linear_model.RidgeCV(fit_intercept=True, normalize=True, alphas = alphas).fit(X_train, y_train)
    ridge = linear_model.Ridge(fit_intercept=True, normalize=True, alpha = round(ridge_cv.alpha_,3)).fit(X_train, y_train)
    mse['Ridge'].append(np.mean((ridge.predict(X_test) - y_test) ** 2))
    
    ### Lasso Regression
    lasso_cv = linear_model.LassoCV(fit_intercept=True, normalize=True, alphas=alphas).fit(X_train, y_train)
    lasso = linear_model.Lasso(fit_intercept=True, normalize=True, alpha = round(lasso_cv.alpha_,3)).fit(X_train, y_train)
    mse['Lasso'].append(np.mean((lasso.predict(X_test) - y_test) ** 2))
    
    ### Bayesian Ridge Regression
    bay = linear_model.BayesianRidge(fit_intercept=True, normalize=True).fit(X_train, y_train)
    mse['Bayesian'].append(np.mean((bay.predict(X_test) - y_test) ** 2))
    
    ### Polynomial Regression
    pol = Pipeline([('poly', PolynomialFeatures(degree=2)),
                    ('linear', linear_model.LinearRegression(fit_intercept=True, normalize=True))]).fit(X_train, y_train)
    mse['Polynomial'].append(np.mean((pol.predict(X_test) - y_test) ** 2))
In [331]:
mse_mean = {k: np.mean(mse[k]) for k in models}
print 'MSE models means'
for k, v in mse_mean.iteritems():
    print round(v,6),'\t', k
print '\nThe model with the minimum MSE', min(mse_mean.values()),'is', min(mse_mean, key=mse_mean.get)

In [332]:
y_pred = []
for i in range(1,len(df_ar.index)):
    X_train = df_ar.iloc[:i]
    X_test = df_ar.iloc[[i]]
    y_train = gt_ts.iloc[:i]
    y_test = gt_ts.iloc[[i]]
    ridge_cv = linear_model.RidgeCV(fit_intercept=True, normalize=True, alphas = alphas).fit(X_train, y_train)
    ridge = linear_model.Ridge(fit_intercept=True, normalize=True, alpha = round(ridge_cv.alpha_,3)).fit(X_train, y_train)
    y_pred.append(ridge.predict(X_test)[0])

Note and conclusion¶

In this last case we have seen thata a simpler model, such as Lasso, is better to make prediction of a series.

Furthermore, we have seen the role of the autoregressive process of order 1, previously in the ACF and PACF plot and after in the model estimate.

To reduce the work of download data from wikipedia, we could drop out the night views and we don't loose information about our research.

The difference with the paper is mainly due to:

  • population in Italy don't use a lot the pc and in particular internet. Without internet the people with flu don't search information on the net;
  • the time series have one year extra;
  • the time series are of all the years and not only the flu seasons (294 obs vs 140 our obs);
